            <definition xml:id="def-Pentagon">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <m>\textbf{pentagon }</m>" comes from the 
                        <em>Greek</em> words "<term>penta</term>," meaning five, and "<term>gon</term>," meaning angle.
                           
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore, 
                            
                        
                        

                        
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A <m>\textbf{pentagon }</m> is a flat, closed shape that has five straight sides and five angles.
                    </p>

                </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
                <term>Key Takeaway</term>

            </p>
            
            <p>
                <ul>
                    
                   
                    <li>

                        <p>
                            A regular pentagon has equal sides and angles. It's aea is given by: <me>
                                \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter} \times \text{Apothem}
                            </me>
                        </p>
                       
                        <p>
                            Where <m>\text{Perimeter}= \text{Length} \times \text{Sides}</m> 
                            and <m>\text{Apothem }</m>is the distance from the center of a regular polygon to aside. 
                        </p>
                       
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find the area of the figure below:
                    </p>
                    <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image label="pentagon3">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1]
                             % Define coordinates manually to approximate a regular pentagon
                            \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                            \coordinate (B) at (3,0);
                            \coordinate (C) at (3.7,2.3);
                            \coordinate (D) at (1.5,4);
                            \coordinate (E) at (-0.7,2.3);
                            \coordinate (Center) at (1.5,1.7); % Approximate center
                            \coordinate (MidAB) at (1.5,0);     % Midpoint of base

                            % Draw and fill the pentagon
                            \filldraw[draw=brown!80!black, fill=white, very thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- (E) -- cycle;

                            % Apothem line
                            \draw[thick, gray] (Center) -- (MidAB);
                            \filldraw[gray] (Center) circle (1pt); % Center point

                            % Apothem label
                            \node at (1.1,1.1) {\footnotesize 12.4 ft};

                            % Side length label
                            \draw[very thick] (A) -- (B) node[midway, below, font=\footnotesize]{18 ft};

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                       
                    </image>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        To find the area of the given pentagon, we use the formula:
                        <me>
                            \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter} \times  \text{apothem}
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                       Since <m>\text{Apothem} = 12.4 \, \text{ft}\, \text{and}\,\text{Side length} = 18\, \text{ ft} </m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>\text{Perimeter}=5 \times 18\, \text{ ft}=90 \, \text{ft}</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore,
                    </p>
                    
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            
                            <mrow> \text{Area}=\amp \frac{1}{2} \times 90 \times 12.4</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp  45 \times 12.4</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp  558 \, \text{ft}^2</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                   
                </solution>
            </example>
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A gardener is designing a regular pentagonal flower bed. Each side of the flower bed is <m>6\, \text{m}</m>, 
                        and the distance from the center of the flower bed to the midpoint of a side  is <m>4.1 \, \text{m}</m>. Find the area of the flower bed.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Recall:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter} \times  \text{apothem}</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{2} \times 5 \times 6 \times 4.1</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp  15 \times 4.1</mrow>
                            <mrow> =\amp  61.5 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                    
                </solution>
            </example>
            <example>
