        <definition xml:id="def-Hexagon">
            <statement>
               <p>
                The word "<m>\textbf{hexagon}</m>" comes from the <em>Greek</em> words 
                "<term>hexa</term>," which means six, and "<term>gon</term>," which means corner or angle.  
            </p>
            <p>
                A <m>\textbf{hexagon}</m> is a flat shape with six straight sides and six corners (angles).  
            </p>


            </statement>
        </definition>
        <p>
            <term>Key Takeaway</term>
        </p>
        <p>
            Below is a figure of a regular hexagon.It has six equal sides and equal angles.
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="hexagon">
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                % Define hexagon vertices
                \foreach \angle in {0,60,...,300} {
                    \coordinate (v\angle) at (\angle:2cm);
                }

                % Draw hexagon
                \draw[thick, fill=blue!10] (v0) -- (v60) -- (v120) -- (v180) -- (v240) -- (v300) -- cycle;

                % Draw center to vertices (optional)
                \draw[dashed, gray] (0,0) -- (v0);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (0,0) -- (v60);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (0,0) -- (v120);

                % Draw and label apothem
                \draw[red, very thick, |-|] (0,0) -- (30:1.732cm) node[midway, above, sloped] {Apothem (a)};
                
                % Label one side
                \draw[|&lt;-&gt;|, rotate=20,thick] (-0.9,-1) ++(-40:1.9cm) -- ++(40:1.9cm) 
                node[midway, below, rotate=60] {Side (s)};

                % Center dot
                \filldraw (0,0) circle (1pt) node[below right] {Center};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
            
        </image>
        
        <p>
           It's area is given by:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\text{Area}=\frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter (P)} \times \text{apothem}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Where <m>\text{Perimeter} = \text{Length} \times \text{Number of sides}</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Or}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            If the apothem and the side is known, use:<me>
                \text{Area} = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2
            </me>
            
        </p>
        
        <p>
            Where <m>\text{s}</m> is the length of one side of the hexagon.
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   Find the area of the hexagon below.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="hexagon3">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (0:2) -- (60:2) -- (120:2) -- (180:2) -- (240:2) -- (300:2) -- cycle;
                        \filldraw  (0,0) circle (1pt) ;
                        \foreach \angle in {60,120}
                            \draw (0,0) -- (\angle:2);
                        \node at (0,2) {4 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>

                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The side length of the hexagon is <m>4 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 4^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 16</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 24\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 41.57c\text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
               
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Bees build honeycombs using hexagonal cells. If each cell has a side 
                    length of <m>7.5 \, \text{mm}</m>, what is the area of one cell?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The side length of the hexagonal cell is <m>7.5 \, \text{mm}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times (7.5)^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 56.25</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 146.1417869 </mrow>
                        <mrow>= \amp 146.142\, \text{km}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    This implies that, the area of one hexagonal cell is approximately <m>{\color{black}146.41 \, \text{km}^2}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                   The figure below shows a regular hexagon with center x.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="hexagon4">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
